snippet.textDisplay:
Hi SortedFood Team,

I've been looking for (and failing to find) a foodie series that revolves around a dozen or so versatile ingredients - or whatever is a reasonable amount for a standard "food shopping trip". And then each episode focuses on a few of those ingredients to make a great dish. Great content for students or just people who dont want to have to buy a whole pack of some exotic mushroom only to use just half of it for one recipe. Once the series has been completed, those who have watched it can consistently buy the same things but still have a variety of meal ideas in their arsenal to get them through each and every day :D Is that perhaps something that maybe you can do?

Just a thought :D

snippet.textDisplay:
Here's the thing. As a final result, it reminds me of Aglio e Olio (especially with the comments that it needed a hit of lemon). And bravo to Barry, pasta is at its best when it's simple. It can be tempting to overcomplicate things by introducing a lot of herbs, meats, and extra bells and whistles, but equally it can excel with just oil, garlic, and lemon. Simple ingredients paired up excellently is always the goal.


Jamie: Good show, perhaps his best in the series. I think despite any claims, he does great in the 1st spot. Even if it's just prep work, it's important work that doesn't always require setting pace for everyone else. Sometimes it's just about making the next guy's life easier. "Work as a team." Finally someone at least said the way to do well at this game. Nobody should be gunning for their own points, they should be going for what helps the team most at that point in time while still being a good show. Absolutely deserved the 8.5. Room to improve for certain, but a solid B. 8.5 was well earned.

Barry: A weaker than average performance, but I think he underrated himself actually. For many sauces, you need a good base and although the garlic bread didn't pan out, the onions left the door open and ready to move for Mike. And nobody dislikes roasted garlic. A guy who knows good pasta, and tried to narrow it down to a set dish. He earned a solid 5. A failing grade here, but one that shows skill and capability with the material.


Mike: It was his turn to fall into the pepper trap. There's a lot of great flavor in roasted peppers, but unless you're in the first couple slots, it seems like you guys just never really have the time necessary to make that work. But that said, didn't fail the team either, even if trying to veer into Spanish at that point was a bit late for a curveball. If nothing else, props for thinking ahead and leaving a clue for the chefs. 4 on the scoreboard. It wasn't terrible, and there was skill involved or at the worst raw ambition alone. But there was a lot of room to improve, and time could have been better spent. Just don't ever think you're bad at this. It's a different type of intelligence needed for each role on the team, and sometimes you're an ace in one, and a dud in the others. Just need the right theme and slot to really shine.


Ben: Probably his weakest performance in a PIO, but that's not necessarily his fault. There were things that had to get done and ate time that could have been spent fixing the dish's direction. The pasta had to be rolled and cut. it had to be ready to go for James, because there just weren't any options left. If there were any things that would have made it easier was having a sauce direction lined up ahead of time, or at the least water ready for the pot. But getting stuck doing prep so late in the game meant he just didn't have the minutes to do all the foundational work as well as the directing. I give a 6. Just below passing, and only because he's set the bar so high for himself before.


James: The classic fixing problem. You're the last man on the team and you've gotta pull out a win with whatever you've got, even if it's just some toasty vegetables, raw pasta and hazelnuts. He tried his best, wrangled it together, and even if it wasn't the best sauce imaginable, it was a functional one. I give a 7. As always this slot is either the absolute hero, or depressing because it was such a strong attempt to fix the ship before it sank.
